        "<p>I $<$ II $<$ III $<$ IV</p>\n",
        "<p>I $<$ II $<$ IV $<$ III</p>\n",
        "<p>IV $<$ I $<$ II $<$ III</p>\n",
        "<p>IV $<$ II $<$ I $<$ III</p>"
      ],
      "correctOption": 2,
      "solution": "<p>$$ \\text { The structure of all four alcohols is given below. } $$</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxrj0/5f738ebc-37b3-46ab-b4b9-d1c311cd589f/47e18dc0-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxrj1.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxrj0/5f738ebc-37b3-46ab-b4b9-d1c311cd589f/47e18dc0-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxrj1.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2006 Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 1 English Explanation 1\">The 1, 2-dihydroxybenzene has second OH group attached at ortho position. The 1, 2-dihydroxybenzene will participate in intramolecular hydrogen bonding as both OH groups are attached at adjacent position as shown below.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxshc/ed779f82-e6b3-4af5-847f-74a0fcb2d50e/489e2700-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxshd.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxshc/ed779f82-e6b3-4af5-847f-74a0fcb2d50e/489e2700-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxshd.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2006 Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 1 English Explanation 2\">Whereas 1, 3-dihydroxybenzene and 1, 4-dihydroxybenzene form intermolecular hydrogen bonding as shown below:</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxte4/2f13fd8b-bbd1-49ce-a961-c8645c5ee90e/495234c0-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxte5.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxte4/2f13fd8b-bbd1-49ce-a961-c8645c5ee90e/495234c0-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxte5.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2006 Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 1 English Explanation 3\">$$ \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\, \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\, \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\, \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\, \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\, \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\, \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\, \\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\text { Intermolecular } \\mathrm{H} \\text { bonding in 1, 4-dihydroxybenzene } $$</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxug0/e37a6561-95bb-46ae-9c1c-5415442b907c/4a225600-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxug1.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mgtbxug0/e37a6561-95bb-46ae-9c1c-5415442b907c/4a225600-aa82-11f0-a104-c55ff33b3376/file-jaoe38c1mgtbxug1.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2006 Chemistry - Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers Question 1 English Explanation 4\">The strength of intermolecular hydrogen bonding is higher in 1, 4-dihydroxybenzene as compared to that of 1,3-dihydroxybenzene and 1,2-dihydroxybenzene. Thestrengthofhydrogen bonding is higher in 1, 3-dihydroxybenzene than 1,2-dihydroxybenzene.</p>\n<p>The monohydroxy benzene will not participate in hydrogen bonding; hence, will have least boiling point.</p>\n<p>Also, the strength of intermolecular hydrogen bonding is higher than that of intramolecular hydrogen bonding. Hence, 1, 4-dihydroxybenzene has highest stability amongst four compounds. The correct order of these four compounds in terms of increasing boiling points is hydroxy benzene, 1, 2-dihydroxybenzene, 1, 3-dihydroxybenzene and 1,4-dihydroxybenzene.</p>\n<p>The increasing order of boiling points of above mentioned alcohols is IV $&lt;$ I $&lt;$ II $&lt;$ III.</p>",
      "marks": 3,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "topic": "Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers"
    },
